<p><b>Tulum</b> ( (<b>Tulu'um</b> in <a href="/wiki/Yucatec_Maya_language" title="Yucatec Maya language">Modern Maya</a>)&#160;; in <a href="/wiki/Spanish_orthography" title="Spanish orthography">Spanish orthography</a>, <b>Tulum</b>) is the site of a <a href="/wiki/Pre-Columbian" title="Pre-Columbian">Pre-Columbian</a> <a href="/wiki/Maya_civilization" title="Maya civilization">Maya</a> <a href="/wiki/Defensive_wall" title="Defensive wall">walled city</a> serving as a major port for <a href="/wiki/Cob%C3%A1" title="Cobá" class="mw-redirect">Cobá</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-apub_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-apub-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Ruins" title="Ruins">ruins</a> are located on 12-meter (39&#160;ft) cliffs, along the east coast of the <a href="/wiki/Yucat%C3%A1n_Peninsula" title="Yucatán Peninsula">Yucatán Peninsula</a> on the <a href="/wiki/Caribbean_Sea" title="Caribbean Sea">Caribbean Sea</a> in the state of <a href="/wiki/Quintana_Roo" title="Quintana Roo">Quintana Roo</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-apub_0-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-apub-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> One of the best-preserved coastal Maya sites, Tulum is today a popular site for <a href="/wiki/Tourism" title="Tourism">tourists</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-apub_0-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-apub-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
